I was shocked to discover this morning that this is to be my 200th blog post. Wow! It has been a good run so far since I restarted the Dead Programmer Society in 2006, and I really appreciate the awesome feedback and support that I have received from the community.
To commemorate this personal event, here is a list of my top 10 favorite posts, in no particular order:
1. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d Rather Be A Jazz Programmer&rdquo;

According to a recent eWeek article, there will be four times more Ruby programmers within five years. Before all the haters start making cracks about it going from one thousand to four thousand professional Rubyists, here is a juicy bit from Mark Driver, Gartner analyst:
 &ldquo;There are under one million professional Ruby developers now and we&rsquo;re projecting there will be four million plus by 2013.&rdquo;
 And oh yeah, what about that whole &ldquo;Ruby is for hobbyists&rdquo; misinformation campaign?

I was wading thru my daily ration of VC blogs just now, when something caught my eye. Or I perhaps I should say, I was &ldquo;submerged, weightless, suspended in the tepid depths of the thing&hellip; in a state of perfect sensory deprivation, when all at once an extraordinary thing happened: I noticed something!&quot;
(Thank you Mr. Wolfe)
There is the midst of Fred (A VC)&rsquo;s 30 thoughts at 30,000 feet, it was:

Yet more wisdom about user experience and interface design from the Signal Vs. Noise blog, this time debunking the mistaken idea that a good user interface has anything to do with just drawing a pretty picture, and handing it over to someone to implement.
One phrase in particular really caught my attention, &ldquo;our designers apply their talents to the native materials of the web.&rdquo;
Now, I am not trying to pick on Photoshop people here, but how can you design an interface that is interactive, without using interactive tools to do so?

I have been enjoying some real world fun with my wife and son on the north shore of Hawaii the last few days, and so I have not had time or inclination to post anything.
But I am back in action now, and there will be lots of high-tech fun at RailsConf next week.
Oh, but island life is beautiful. I already miss it&hellip;

Jeff Atwood at the Coding Horror blog links to a great introduction to Bayes' Theorem.
If indeed as has been claimed &ldquo;Google uses Bayesian filtering the way Microsoft uses the if statement,&quot; we should all be well versed in the work of the mysterious Reverend Bayes&hellip;
I have been playing around intermittently with an interesting application of Bayesian classification for a couple of years. Perhaps this will inspire me to actually finish it up enough to put it up on the web.

